Understanding Chicago's Demographic Characteristics

Matthew Grady

July 10, 2021

Overview

In this work sample, I'll use R to gather and visualize demographic data for the City of Chicago. Here's my plan:

  • I'll use the tidycensus package to access data from the U.S. Census Bureau's American Community Survey1;
  • I'll use a bar plot to visualize Chicago's overall racial and ethnic composition; and
  • I'll create a choropleth map to show how Chicago's different racial and ethnic groups are distributed across the city;

Before getting started, I'll load the R packages I plan to use.

library(tidyverse)
library(tidycensus)
library(tigris)
library(rgdal)
library(stringr)
library(gridExtra)
library(extrafont)
library(sf)
library(rgeos)
library(ggrepel)
loadfonts(device = "win", quiet = TRUE)

Getting the American Commmunity Survey Data

First, I'd like to create a bar plot showing Chicago's overall racial and ethnic composition. To do so, I'll access demographic data from the American Community Survey using the tidycensus package.

Using the code below, I'll request population estimates for every census designated place in Illinois, by race and Hispanic or Latino origin. Specifically, I'll request 2015-2019 five-year population estimates, which are based on data collected over a five-year period. Then, I'll subset data for the City of Chicago.

city.dem = get_acs(geography = "place", 
              table="B03002",   # The table with the race data
              state = c('IL'),
              survey = 'acs5',  # ACS, 5-year estimates
              year = 2019)

city.dem = city.dem %>%
  filter(NAME %in% c('Chicago city, Illinois'))  # subset Chicago

The Census Bureau treats race and Hispanic or Latino origin as separate variables. For this analysis, I'll create my own race variable by classifying residents into the following mutually exclusive groups:

  • American Indian and Alaska Native alone (not Hispanic or Latino)
  • Asian alone (not Hispanic or Latino)
  • Black or African American alone (not Hispanic or Latino)
  • Native Hawaiian and Other Pacific Islander alone (not Hispanic or Latino)
  • White alone (not Hispanic or Latino)
  • Some other race alone (not Hispanic or Latino)
  • Two or more races (not Hispanic or Latino)
  • Hispanic or Latino (any race)
city.dem = city.dem %>%
  filter(variable %in% c('B03002_001','B03002_003','B03002_004','B03002_005',
                         'B03002_006','B03002_007','B03002_008','B03002_009',
                         'B03002_012')) %>%  # the group population estimates
  mutate(race = as.factor(recode(variable,
    B03002_001="Total",
    B03002_003="White",
    B03002_004="Black or African American",
    B03002_005="American Indian and Alaska Native",
    B03002_006="Asian",
    B03002_007="Native Hawaiian and Other Pacific Islander",
    B03002_008="Some other race",
    B03002_009="Two or more races",
    B03002_012="Hispanic or Latino")
  ))

For plotting purposes, I'll retain the groups that make up at least one percent of Chicago's population.

city.dem = city.dem %>%
  mutate(Percent = estimate / estimate[race=='Total']*100) %>%  # calculate %
  filter(Percent >= 1 & race != 'Total')  # keep if gte 1%

Next, I'll order the levels of the race variable based on group size, and create some nicely formatted labels that I'll use when I make the bar plot.

city.dem$race = factor(city.dem$race, levels=c('White','Black or African American','Hispanic or Latino',
                                               'Asian','Two or more races')) # order factor levels

city.dem$labels = paste(as.character(round(city.dem$Percent, 0)), '%', sep='') # labels

Chicago's Racial and Ethnic Composition

Now, I'm ready to create the bar plot. I'll start by specifying the core sytax for the plot.

bar.plot.dem = ggplot(city.dem, aes(x=race, y=Percent, fill=race)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", color='gray70', size=1) +
  scale_fill_manual(values=c('#F8766D','#7CAE00','#C77CFF','#00BFC4','#F564E3')) +
  scale_y_continuous(name=NULL, limits=c(0,40), breaks=seq(0,40,10), expand=c(0,0)) +
  scale_x_discrete(name=NULL, labels=c('White','Black or\nAfrican American','Hispanic or\nLatino',
                                       'Asian','Two or more\nraces')) +
  geom_text(aes(label=labels), vjust=-.5, size=4, family='Segoe UI', color='gray20') +
  labs(title="Chicago has roughly equal numbers of White, Black, and Latino residents",
       subtitle="Chicago's Overall Racial and Ethnic Composition",
       caption = "\n\nSource: American Community Survey, 2015-2019 five-year estimates.")

Next, I'll make some formatting changes to the plot using the theme command.

bar.plot.dem = bar.plot.dem +
  theme(
    panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    legend.position = "none",
    plot.title = element_text(size=12, face='bold', hjust=.5, family='Segoe UI'),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(size=12, hjust=.5, family='Segoe UI'),
    plot.caption = element_text(size=9, family='Segoe UI', color='gray30', hjust=0),
    axis.title = element_text(family='Segoe UI'),
    axis.text.y = element_blank(),
    axis.text.x = element_text(family='Segoe UI', size=11),
    axis.ticks = element_blank(),
    panel.background = element_rect(color='gray70', fill='gray94', size=1)
  )

Now, I'll make a secondary bar plot that I can set within the primary one. The secondary plot will show the most common ethnic origins for Chicago's Hispanic or Latino residents. I'll first use the tidycensus package to get the origin data from the American Community Survey.

city.hisp = get_acs(geography = "place",  
                    table="B03001", # The table with the origin estimates
                    state = c('IL'),
                    survey = 'acs5',  # ACS, 5-year estimates
                    year = 2019)  # 2015-2019 5-year estimates

city.hisp = city.hisp %>%
  filter(NAME %in% c('Chicago city, Illinois')) # Keep Chicago only

I'll select the five most common ethnic origins to represent in the bar plot: Mexican, Puerto Rican, Ecuadorian, Guatemalan, and Cuban.

city.hisp = city.hisp %>%
  filter(variable %in% c('B03001_003','B03001_004','B03001_005','B03001_021',
                         'B03001_010','B03001_006')) %>%  # the group estimates
  mutate(origin = as.factor(recode(variable,
                                   B03001_003="Total",
                                   B03001_004='Mexican',
                                   B03001_005='Puerto Rican',
                                   B03001_021='Ecuadorian',
                                   B03001_010='Guatemalan',
                                   B03001_006='Cuban')
  ))

Next, I'll determine each group's share of the total Hispanic or Latino population, and re-order the levels of the factor accordingly.

city.hisp = city.hisp %>%
  mutate(Percent = estimate / estimate[origin=='Total']*100) %>% # calculate %
  filter(origin != 'Total')  # remove the 'total' column

city.hisp = city.hisp[order(city.hisp$estimate),]
city.hisp$origin = factor(city.hisp$origin, levels=city.hisp$origin) # define the levels

Now, I'll create the bar plot showing the most common origins for the Hispanic or Latino residents. I'll start by specifying the core syntax for the plot.

city.hisp$labels = paste(as.character(round(city.hisp$Percent, 0)), '%', sep='') # create nice labels

bar.plot.hisp = ggplot(city.hisp, aes(x=origin, y=Percent)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", fill='#C77CFF', color='#C77CFF', width=.75) +
  scale_y_continuous(name=NULL, limits=c(0,90), breaks=seq(0,80,10), expand=c(0,0)) +
  scale_x_discrete(name=NULL) +
  geom_text(aes(label=labels), hjust=-.15, size=2.75, family='Segoe UI', color='gray20') +
  coord_flip()

Next, I'll make some formatting changes.

bar.plot.hisp = bar.plot.hisp +
  theme(
    plot.margin = margin(5.5, 3, 1, 5.5, "pt"),
    panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    legend.position = "none",
    plot.title = element_text(family='Segoe UI', size=8, face='bold', hjust=0),
    axis.title = element_text(family='Segoe UI'),
    axis.text.y = element_text(family='Segoe UI', size=9),
    axis.text.x = element_blank(),
    axis.ticks = element_blank(),
    panel.background = element_rect(color=NA, fill=NA),
    plot.background = element_rect(fill='gray98', color='gray70', size=1.25) 
  )

And finally, I'll output the final product. I'll use the annotation_custom command to set the secondary bar plot within the primary one.

bar.plot.dem = bar.plot.dem +
  geom_segment(aes(x=3.35, y=26, xend=3.6, yend=26), color='gray70', size=1) +
  geom_segment(aes(x=3.59, y=26, xend=3.59, yend=32.1), color='gray70', size=1) +
  geom_segment(aes(x=3.6, y=32, xend=3.75, yend=32), color='gray70', size=1,
               arrow = arrow(length=unit(.015, "npc"), type='closed')) 

bar.plot.dem = bar.plot.dem + 
  annotation_custom( 
    ggplotGrob(bar.plot.hisp),  
    xmin=3.75, xmax=5.5, ymin=26, ymax=38.5
  )
bar.plot.dem

As I indicate in the plot title, Chicago has roughly equal numbers of White, Black, and Hispanic or Latino residents. Asian residents also make up a sizeable share of the population, at 7%. The majority of Hispanic or Latino residents indicate they are of Mexican origin, but there is also a sizeable percentage who are of Puerto Rican descent.

Geographic Distribution of Chicago's Racial and Ethnic Groups

Next, I'll create a choropleth map to show how Chicago's largest racial and ethnic groups are distributed across the city. I'll start by using the tidycensus package to get population estimates, by group, for census tracts within the two Illinois counties that overlap with Chicago: Cook and DuPage. I'll use the same basic code as before, except that I'll specify "tract" as the desired geographic level.

tract.dem = get_acs(geography = "tract",  # Get tract-level data
              table = "B03002",  
              year = 2019,  
              survey = 'acs5', # get 5-year estimates
              state = 'IL', 
              county = c('Cook','DuPage')) # Cook and DuPage counties

Next, I'll create my own race variable in the same way that I did earlier.

tract.dem = tract.dem %>%
  filter(variable %in% c('B03002_001','B03002_003','B03002_004','B03002_005',
                         'B03002_006','B03002_007','B03002_008','B03002_009',
                         'B03002_012')) %>%
  mutate(race = as.factor(recode(variable,
                                 B03002_001="Total",
                                 B03002_003="White",
                                 B03002_004="Black or African American",
                                 B03002_005="American Indian and Alaska Native",
                                 B03002_006="Asian",
                                 B03002_007="Native Hawaiian and Other Pacific Islander",
                                 B03002_008="Some other race",
                                 B03002_009="Two or more races",
                                 B03002_012="Hispanic or Latino")
  ))

For each census tract, I'll calculate each group's share of the population. Then, I'll identify the largest group in each tract. I'll use this information when I create the choropleth map.

tract.dem.largest = tract.dem %>%
  group_by(GEOID) %>%
  mutate(race.pct=estimate / estimate[race=='Total']*100) %>%
  filter(race != 'Total') %>%
  select(GEOID, race, estimate, race.pct) %>%
  slice(which.max(estimate))

In order to create the map, I need to get shape files of the census tracts in Cook and DuPage counties. I'll access these shape files from the Census Bureau using the tigris package.

Cook.tracts = tracts(state = 'IL', county='Cook', cb=F, progress_bar=F, class='sp') # Cook County tracts
DuPage.tracts = tracts(state = 'IL', county='DuPage', cb=F, progress_bar=F, class='sp') # DuPage County tracts

tracts = rbind(Cook.tracts, DuPage.tracts) # combine the two counties

The combined census tract shape file covers the entire area of Cook and DuPage counties, which extends well beyond the City of Chicago boundary. Because I want the map to include Chicago only, I'll need to trim the shape file. In order to do so, I'll first import a shape file that contains the Chicago boundary. I retrieved the file from the City of Chicago Data Portal2. I'll think of the boundary file as a cookie cutter that I'll use to trim off the portions of Cook and DuPage counties that lie outside of the city.

chi = readOGR("C:/Users/Matt/Desktop/IL shape files/Chicago", "Chicago shape file", verbose=F)

Next, I'll change the coordinate reference system for the Chicago boundary file, and then use the intersect command from the raster package to trim the census tract shape file along the city boundary.

chi.sf = st_as_sf(chi) # convert to sf file
chi.sf = st_transform(chi.sf, "+proj=longlat +ellps=WGS84 +datum=WGS84") # change CRS
chi = as(chi.sf, 'Spatial') # convert back to shape file
chi.fort = fortify(chi, region='name') # fortify the shape file

library(raster)
crs(chi) = crs(tracts) # ensure same CRS
chi.tracts = intersect(tracts, chi)  # trim tract shape file
detach("package:raster", unload=TRUE)

Now, I'll limit the data frame that contains the demographic data for the census tracts to tracts that are fully or partially within Chicago. Then, I'll add the demographic data to the census tract shape file. Note that I'll also create a fortified version of the shape file, which I'll use to make the choropleth map with ggplot.

tract.dem.largest = tract.dem.largest[tract.dem.largest$GEOID %in% chi.tracts$GEOID,] # limit to Chicago tracts

chi.tracts.fort = fortify(chi.tracts, region='GEOID') # create fortified file

tract.dem.largest$id = tract.dem.largest$GEOID
tr2 = merge(chi.tracts.fort, tract.dem.largest, by='id', all.x=T, all.y=F) # add data to shape file
tr2 = tr2[order(tr2$order),]  # retain original order

Finally, I'll categorize each tract based on its largest group. When I create the map, I'll color each census tract based on its largest group, and shade each tract based on that group's share of the tract's population. If a group makes up more than 75% of a tract's population, I'll use the darkest shade of the corresponding color. I'll also identify census tracts that have no residents so I can shade them in light gray.

tr2$cat3[tr2$race == 'White' & tr2$race.pct >= 75] = 'White >= 75%'
tr2$cat3[tr2$race == 'White' & tr2$race.pct < 75] = 'White < 75%'
tr2$cat3[tr2$race == 'Black or African American' & tr2$race.pct >= 75] = 'Black >= 75%'
tr2$cat3[tr2$race == 'Black or African American' & tr2$race.pct < 75] = 'Black < 75%'
tr2$cat3[tr2$race == 'Hispanic or Latino' & tr2$race.pct >= 75] = 'Latino >= 75%'
tr2$cat3[tr2$race == 'Hispanic or Latino' & tr2$race.pct < 75] = 'Latino < 75%'
tr2$cat3[tr2$race == 'Asian' & tr2$race.pct >= 75] = 'Asian >= 75%'
tr2$cat3[tr2$race == 'Asian' & tr2$race.pct < 75] = 'Asian < 75%'
tr2$cat3[tr2$estimate ==0] = 'No residents'

tr2$cat3 = factor(tr2$cat3, levels=c('White < 75%','White >= 75%','Black < 75%','Black >= 75%',
                                     'Latino < 75%','Latino >= 75%','Asian < 75%','Asian >= 75%','No residents'))

Now I'm ready to create the choropleth map. I'll start by specifying the core syntax for the map.

race.map = ggplot() +
  geom_polygon(data=subset(tr2, hole==FALSE),
               aes(x=long, y=lat, group=group, fill=cat3), 
               color='gray80', size = 0.05) + 
  geom_polygon(data=subset(tr2, hole==TRUE),
               aes(x=long, y=lat, group=group), fill='white',
               color='gray80', size = 0.05) + 
  geom_polygon(data=chi.fort, 
               aes(x=long, y=lat, group=group), 
               color='gray30', size=0.45, fill=NA) + 
  scale_fill_manual(values=c(alpha("#F8766D", alpha=.5), "#F8766D", alpha("#7CAE00", alpha=.5), "#7CAE00",
                             alpha("#C77CFF", alpha=.5), "#C77CFF",alpha("#00BFC4", alpha=.5), "#00BFC4", 'gray85'), 
                    labels = c('less than 75%','75% or more','less than 75%',
                               '75% or more','less than 75%','75% or more',
                               'less than 75%','75% or more','no residents')) +
  scale_y_continuous(expand=c(0, 0), limits=c(41.64454-.01, 42.02304+.01),
                     breaks=seq(41.6,42.1,.01)) +
  scale_x_continuous(expand=c(0, 0), limits=c(-88.07, -87.39)) +
  labs(title="How are Chicago's largest racial groups distributed across the city?",
       subtitle="Distribution of Race in the City of Chicago, by Census Tract",
       caption = "Source: American Community Survey, 2015-2019 five-year estimates.") +
  guides(fill = guide_legend(ncol=1)) +
  coord_quickmap(clip = 'off')

Next, I'll make some formatting changes using the theme command.

race.map = race.map +
  theme(
    plot.margin=grid::unit(c(7,0,7,0), "pt"),
    legend.position = 'none',
    axis.title = element_blank(),
    axis.text = element_blank(),
    axis.ticks = element_blank(),
    panel.background = element_rect(fill=NA, color=NA),
    plot.background = element_rect(fill='gray97', color='gray65'),
    panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    plot.title = element_text(size=12, face='bold', hjust=.5, family='Segoe UI'),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(size=12, hjust=.5, family='Segoe UI'),
    plot.caption = element_text(size=9, family='Segoe UI', color='gray30', hjust=.95)
  )

Now, I'll create a custom map legend. The legend will consist of a series of colored rectangles and annotations. I'll start by creating the rectangles.

race.map = race.map +

Now, I'll use some annotations to label the rectangles.

race.map = race.map +

race.map

There are a couple of things that stand out to me when I study the map. First, the fact that the map has no labels makes it hard for me to get my bearings, even through I live in Chicago and am familiar with the city's geography. I'll address this problem in a moment by adding some labels to the map.

Second, because each census tract can only be one color, the map creates the impression that each tract is homogeneous with respect to race and ethnicity. In reality, there are a number of racially diverse census tracts in the city that aren't really identifiable in this map. That said, it is also clear from the map that tracts with Black or Latino pluralities are often predominantly Black or Latino. For example, most of the tracts with Black pluralities are shaded dark green, which indicates they are ...

Chicago's Community Areas

Chicago can be divided into 77 Community Areas. I'd like to overlay the Community Area boundaries on the map, and label them for reference. I'll start by importing the Community Area boundary file, which I downloaded from the Chicago Data Portal. Then, I'll change the file's coordinate reference system and create a fortified version.

coms = readOGR("C:/Users/Matt/Desktop/Matt/2021-05-31/2. Chicago demographics/Shape files", "geo_export_0fa5b834-5cf4-45b0-ad72-57c2ff4502a8", verbose=F)

coms.sf = st_as_sf(coms)
coms.sf = st_transform(coms.sf, "+proj=longlat +ellps=WGS84 +datum=WGS84") # change CRS
coms = as(coms.sf, 'Spatial')
coms.fort = fortify(coms, region='community') # fortify the shape file

Next, I'll determine the centroid, or geometric center, of each Community Area. Later, I'll use the centroids to position the Community Area labels on the map.

centroids = getSpPPolygonsLabptSlots(coms) # get centroids
coms$X = centroids[,1] # the X coordinate
coms$Y = centroids[,2] # the Y coordinate
cents = data.frame(coms$area_num_1, coms$community, coms$X, coms$Y) # put centroids in a data frame
names(cents) = c('Number','Community Area','X','Y') # rename the columns

Now, I'll add the Community Area boundaries to the map, along with their labels.

race.map = race.map +
  geom_polygon(data=coms.fort, 
               aes(x=long, y=lat, group=group), 
               color='gray30', size=0.40, fill=NA) +
  geom_text_repel(data=cents, aes(x=X, y=Y, label=Number), size=3, color='gray15',
                  nudge_x=0, nudge_y=-0, direction='y', fontface='bold',
                  bg.colour='white', bg.r=.10, force_pull=1, force=0,
                  lineheight=.80)

Next, I'll create a data frame that contains the number and name of each Community Area. Ultimately, I'll use the data frame as a legend the reader can use to identify the Community Areas on the map.

ca.names = cents 
ca.names$`Community Area` = tolower(ca.names$`Community Area`) # clean CA names
ca.names$Number = factor(ca.names$Number, levels=seq(1,77,1))
ca.names$Name = paste(ca.names$Number, ca.names$`Community Area`, sep='.  ')
ca.names = ca.names[order(ca.names$Number),] # order CAs
ca.names = ca.names[, names(ca.names)=='Name']

ca.names = str_to_title(ca.names) 
ca.names2 = data.frame(ca.names[1:39], c(ca.names[40:77],'')) # create legend table

Finally, I'll format the Community Area legend and add it to the map using the annotation_custom command. Then I'll output the final map.

mytheme= ttheme_default(
  core = list(fg_params=list(cex=.64, hjust=0, x=0, fontfamily='Segoe UI'),
              bg_params = list(fill=NA, col=NA)),
  padding = unit(c(2.7, 1.18), "mm"))

ca.table = tableGrob(ca.names2, theme=mytheme, rows=NULL, cols=NULL)

race.map2 = race.map +
  annotation_custom(ca.table, xmin=-88.10, xmax=-87.78, 
                    ymin=41.62, ymax=41.94)

race.map2

To me, the addition of Community Area boundaries really helps. I can identify an area on the map, and then put a name to it.
